{{see also|Isidore of Seville}}
'''Isidorus''' (born c. 139) was a native ancient [[Egypt]]ian [[priest]] in the 2nd century during the [[Roman Egypt|Roman rule in Egypt]]. He led the native Egyptian [[revolt]] against [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] rule during the reign of [[Roman Emperor|emperor]] [[Marcus Aurelius]].<ref>Dio Cassius, [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/72*.html, Epitome 72]</ref>
==Life== According to the Roman historian [[Dio Cassius]], Isidorus surpassed all his contemporaries in bravery while leading the Egyptians in this revolt, most often called the [[Bucolic War]]. It broke out in 172&ndash;173 as a result of oppressive [[taxation]] in the [[Boucolia marshes]] of the [[Nile Delta]]. At first the Egyptians were successful, having defeated the Romans in a pitched battle. After this victory, they almost captured [[Alexandria]], and probably would have taken the city if [[Avidius Cassius]], the governor of [[Syria]], had not been sent against them from the place he governed. Cassius did not dare to attack the rebels while they were united, knowing that they were too numerous and powerful to be defeated; however, he managed to destroy them by separating them from one another. Thus, the [[Rebellion|rebels]] were finally subdued only when they fell to quarreling.
The revolt had bad consequences for Egypt: it caused great damage to the Egyptian economy and marked the beginning of Egypt's economic decline.
