* Channabasavanna Jayanti (Deepavali)

==Literature==
{{Main|Vachana Sahitya}}
{{wide image|Plam leaf of 11th and 12th Century with Vachanas.jpg|750px|align-cap=center|[[Vachana Sahitya]] (also called ''Sharana Sahitya'') on a [[Palm-leaf manuscript|Palm Leaf]]}}

===Lingayat literature===
[[File:Akkamahadevi Vachana2.JPG|thumb|right|A vachana (poem) by [[Akka Mahadevi]]]]
Several works are attributed to the founder of Lingayatism movement, Basava, and these texts are revered in the Lingayat community. In particular, these include various ''Vachana'' (literally, "what is said"){{sfn|Olson|2007|p=239–240}} such as the ''Shat-sthala-vachana'', ''Kala-jnana-vachana'', ''Mantra-gopya'', ''Ghatachakra-vachana'' and ''Raja-yoga-vachana''.{{sfn|Rice|1982|p=53–54}} Saints and Sharanas like Allamaprabhu, Akka Mahadevi, [[Siddarama]] and Basava were at the forefront of this development during the 12th century.

Other important Lingayat literature includes:{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}
* [[Shunyasampadane]]
* [[Mantra Gopya]]
* [[Shunyasampadane|Shunya Sampadane]]
* [[Karana Hasuge]]

The ''[[Basava Purana]]'', a Telugu biographical epic poem which narrates the life story of Basava, was written by [[Palkuriki Somanatha]] in 13th-century, and an updated 14th century Kannada version was written by [[Bhima Kavi]] in 1369. Both are sacred texts in Lingayatism.{{sfn|Rao|Roghair|2014|p=21–23}}

===Vedas and shastras===
Lingayat (Veerashaiva) thinkers rejected the custodial hold of Brahmins over the [[Veda]]s and the [[shastra]]s, but they did not outright reject the Vedic knowledge.{{sfn|Prasad|2012|p=104}}{{sfn|Rao|Roghair|2014|p=7}}{{sfn|Rao|Roghair|2014|p=7}} The 13th-century Telugu Virashaiva poet [[Palkuriki Somanatha]], author of [[Basava Purana]]—a scripture of Veerashaivas, for example asserted, "Virashaivism fully conformed to the [[Vedas]] and the shastras."{{sfn|Prasad|2012|p=104}}{{sfn|Rao|Roghair|2014|p=7-8}} Somanatha repeatedly stated that "he was a scholar of the four Vedas".{{sfn|Rao|Roghair|2014|p=7}}

Lingayatism considers the Vedas as a means, but not the sanctimonious end.{{sfn|McCormack|1963}} It rejected various forms of ritualism and the uncritical adherence to any text including the Vedas.{{sfn|Ishwaran|1980|p=72-76}}

===Anubhava Mantapa===
The ''Anubhava Mantapa'' literally means the "hall of spiritual experience".{{sfn|Schouten|1995|p=1-5}} It has been a Lingayat institution since the time of Basava, serving as an academy of mystics, saints and poet-philosophers for discussion of spiritual and mundane questions of life, in open.{{sfn|Das|2005|p=161-163}} It was the fountainhead of all religious and philosophical thought pertaining to the Lingayata. It was presided over by the mystic Allamaprabhu, and numerous sharanas from all over Karnataka and other parts of India were participants. This institution also helped propagate Lingayatism religious and philosophical thought. Akka Mahadevi, Channabasavanna and Basavanna himself were participants in the [[Anubhava Mantapa]].{{sfn|Schouten|1995|p=1-5}}

==Demographics==
Lingayats today are found predominantly in the state of [[Karnataka]], especially in North and Central Karnataka with a sizeable population native to South Karnataka. Lingayats have been estimated to be about 20% of Karnataka's population.{{sfn|Levinson|Christensen|2002|p=475}}{{refn|group=note|Levinson & Christensen (2002): "The Lingayats are a Hindu sect concentrated in the state of Karnataka (a southern provincial state of India), which covers 191,773 square kilometres. The Lingayats constitute around 20 percent of the total population in that state."{{sfn|Levinson|Christensen|2002|p=475}}}}
& in the state of Maharastra forming for about 9% of state population.

Significant populations are also found in parts of [[Andhra Pradesh]] and [[Telangana]] bordering Karnataka, as well as [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Kerala]] and [[Gujarat]]. The Lingayat diaspora can be found in countries around the world, particularly the [[United States]], [[United Kingdom|Britain]] and [[Australia]].<ref name=Economist_2017_medievalpoet group=web/>

Today, the Lingayat community is a blend of various [[caste]]s, consisting of [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|SC]], [[Other Backward Class|OBC]], [[working class]]es and various [[Vaishya]] castes, that have come together to form the single political entity.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/karnataka/2018/mar/23/lingayat-scs-obcs-may-not-welcome-minority-tag-1791248.html|title=Lingayat SCs, OBCs may not welcome minority tag|work=The New Indian Express|access-date=2018-08-11}}</ref>

