[[File:Jerusalem Arabs selling sechach.tif|thumb|250px|Arabs selling s'chach to Hasidic Jews in Jerusalem, 1930s]]
'''S'chach''' (סכך) is the [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] name for the material used as a roof for a [[sukkah]], used on the [[Jewish holidays|Jewish holiday]] of [[Sukkot]].
S'chach has to derive from things that have "grown from the ground", such as [[Arecaceae|palm]] leaves, [[bamboo]] sticks and [[pine tree]] branches. Some types of wooden slats and other types of [[organic material]] can be used for s'chach, unless they were processed for a different use.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.star-k.org/articles/articles/seasonal/428/undercover-the-halachos-of-schach/|title=Undercover: The Halachos of Schach|website=www.star-k.org|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref> The s'chach must have been disconnected from the ground so, for example, placing a sukkah under the boughs of a tree would render it not valid. As a minimum, the s'chach must be thick enough that it provides more shade than light in the sukkah. As a maximum, there is a concept of being able to see the stars through the s'chach, but the absolute maximum is that rain should be able to penetrate into the sukkah.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oohY_3hMFS8C&pg=PA160&dq=s'chach&hl=en&ei=sdOBTs3IL87Zsgby8ciiDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CD4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=s'chach&f=false|title=Gateway to Judaism: The What, how and why of Jewish Life|first=Mordechai|last=Becher|date=5 May 2018|publisher=Mesorah Publications|accessdate=5 May 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref> If the sukkah is kept year round, the s'chach must be replaced no more than 30 days before Sukkos. It is not necessary to completely remove the s'chach; it would be sufficient to lift each piece of s'chach up one foot or more into the air, and then put it back down.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beingjewish.com/yomtov/sukkos/build.html|title=How Do We Make a Sukkah?|website=www.beingjewish.com|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref>
