'''Yoga Alliance''' is a U.S.-based [[Nonprofit organization|nonprofit]] membership [[Professional association|trade and professional organization]] for [[yoga]] teachers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/01/29/health/yoga-health-concerns/index.html |title=Who should be allowed to teach yoga? &#124; CNN |publisher=CNN.com |date=July 14, 2011 |accessdate=January 29, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yogajournal.com/uncategorized/yoga-alliance-expands-reach/ |title=Yoga Alliance Expands Reach &#124; Yoga Journal |publisher=YogaJournal.com |date=July 14, 2011 |accessdate=May 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name="yogajournal.com">http://www.yogajournal.com/article/teach/how-to-choose-a-yoga-teacher-training-program/ "How to Choose a Yoga Teacher Training Program" hosted at Yoga Journal written by Rachel Brahinsky on AUG 28, 2007, accessed on October 6th, 2014</ref> The organization is headquartered in [[Arlington County, Virginia|Arlington]], [[Virginia]].

Registered Yoga Teacher, a title in the United States that designates a yoga teacher who has received a certain standard of yoga teacher training at a Registered Yoga School, is offered by the Yoga Alliance at the 200-, 300- and 500-hour levels.<ref name="Credentialing" /> As of 2007, there were 9,940 yoga teachers who had met the criteria needed to be registered with Yoga Alliance.<ref name="yogajournal.com" />

According to the Yoga Alliance, the Yoga Alliance Registry is a voluntary credentialing system.<ref name="Credentialing">{{Cite web|title=Credentialing for Teachers|url=https://www.yogaalliance.org/Credentialing/Credentials_for_Teacher/|publisher=Yoga Alliance|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> The teacher registry is not a certification program, but a listing of teachers who meet Yoga Alliance's Requirements for teaching experience and have completed their training at a Registered Yoga School.<ref name="Credentialing" />

